        "headline": "Baker’s Wide Reach: Multiple Communities Respond to Athletic Facilities Old and New",
        "date": "April 26, 2022",
        "byline": "By Amira McKee, Alice Tecotzky, and Amine Bit",
        "pages": {
          "page_0_link": "",
          "Page_0_title": "Despite years of complaints, Bronx residents say Columbia has failed to address intrusive Baker Athletic Complex lights",
          "page_0_cover_img": "https://cloudfront-us-east-1.images.arcpublishing.com/spectator/DKOBI7YZXVHC3ISIFZSJV4VNWU.jpg",
          "page_0_cover_caption": "Violet Mendelsund / Staff Photographer",
          "page_0_heading": "Part 1: Lights",
          "page_0_date": "April 26, 2022",
          "page_0_byline": "By Amira McKee",
          "page_1_link": "",
          "page_1_title": "As Columbia builds a new tennis center, some Inwood residents praise communication, but question the project’s impact",
          "page_1_cover_img": "https://cloudfront-us-east-1.images.arcpublishing.com/spectator/OGYRHBKLK5FSRA5GY4LQFF7C2A.jpg",
          "page_1_cover_caption": "Annie Son / Staff Photographer",
          "page_1_heading": "Part 2: Tennis Center",
          "page_1_date": "April 26, 2022",
          "page_1_byline": "By Alice Tecotzky and Amine Bit"
        },
        "bodies": {
          "page_0": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "When Vanessa Ortiz first moved into 555 Kappock St., a largely retiree community, in the summer of 2017, the excellent views and great natural light made her new Spuyten Duyvil apartment an ideal home. Then, Columbia began its academic year."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "From across the Harlem River and more than a third of a mile away, the stadium lights of Columbia’s Baker Athletic Complex blare through her windows at night. She said she struggles to sleep and relax comfortably in her home, as each night the lights “illuminate everything.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Ortiz is one of hundreds of Bronx residents whose lives have been disrupted by Baker Athletic Complex light pollution. Yet, despite years of persistent tenant advocacy, residents say Columbia has done nothing."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Sima Rabinowitz and her partner were similarly unaware of the severity of the lights when they moved in to 555 Kappock in 2008. Having only seen the apartment in the daytime, they were shocked their first night to find their home bright enough to “read something without turning a light on.” In their time at 555 Kappock,  Rabinowitz and her partner have lived through a variety of lighting schedules on the fields, but, she says, the last few months have been especially challenging."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“It’s very, very intense,” Rabinowitz said. “It’s very hard to relax or rest with really bright artificial light shining in your eyes. … It makes it difficult to see the television, it’s hard to sleep with a bright light shining in your eyes. … It’s just this persistent aggravation.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Before moving to 555 Kappock a year ago, Charlotte Nugent lived in Park Terrace Gardens, another residential building facing Baker Athletic Complex. Though the lights are less intense in her current apartment, she described the light at Park Terrace Gardens as “so bright that it was like broad daylight at 10 p.m.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "image",
              "value": {
                "asset": "image.jpg",
                "credit": "Vanessa Ortiz"
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Once Columbia Athletics began using the field more in September, Ortiz found the brightness and angle of the stadium lights particularly challenging. Though other tenants have been forced to buy blackout curtains, Ortiz said she cannot afford curtains large enough to entirely block the light."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“I don’t know what was the rationale of having them up that high and pointed outward instead of downward,” Ortiz said. “It just feels invasive. And it feels rude. It feels rude to everyone that lives around here. You know, it’s like, we don’t care about you people, we only care about our students who are playing right now.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Ernece B. Kelly, who has lived in 555 Kappock for over 15 years, like Ortiz, first felt the impact of the Baker Athletic Complex lights in 2017. The lights were so disruptive to her sleep that she called 311, hoping to improve her situation. She was told that because Columbia is a private university on private property, little could be done."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "So, in 2017, Kelly reached out to Columbia on her own, with a letter explaining the challenges to her sleep and quality of life posed by the Baker Athletic Complex lights. But, she said, nothing came of it."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Next, Kelly contacted former Bronx 11th district councilperson Andrew Cohen, who addressed a letter to Athletic Director Peter Pilling. Cohen wrote that he received constituent complaints regarding Baker lighting.  Again, she said no progress was made."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“It was difficult for me to get to sleep and stay asleep, so it was a personal issue,” Kelly said. “And in talking to my neighbors, I realized that this isn’t just an issue for me, but it’s an issue for many people who live on the same side of the building that I live on.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "The University could not be reached for comment regarding the lighting at Baker at the time of publication."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Seeing no progress after her or Cohen’s communications, Kelly turned to her fellow residents. She drafted and distributed a petition outlining the harms of the Baker Athletic Complex’s “exceedingly strong lights shining into our homes most weeknights, affecting our quality of life!” From May to July 2018, Ernece visited each apartment facing Columbia fields."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“I would ring the bell and say I’m a neighbor and I’m trying to collect names to approach Columbia University with the issue of the light being a problem for us and I got more than a hundred signatures,” Kelly said. “Most people are interested and willing to sign. And there were some people who said, ‘No, I didn’t want to get involved,’ but they were in that tiny minority.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "The petition, which garnered 109 signatures, demanded Columbia “PLEASE limit [stadium light] use to those hours when there is an activity necessitating their use.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "According to the 2021 Baker Field Agreement Activities Report, the stadium lights run on timers and shut off automatically at 10:30 p.m. every day. Rabinowitz, Ortiz, Kelly, and Tsirkas all said the lights are often on while the field is empty."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“From where I am standing in the window, I can see if there’s even someone running on the track,” Rabinowitz said. “That’s how clear a vision I have of the field. And so I can see at night down there, there’s absolutely nothing happening. There’s no one running, there’s no one grooming the field in a truck, there’s no football players, there’s nothing. And it’s just the light.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "In December 2018, Kelly said the building’s corporate lawyer sent a letter to associate athletics director for facilities operations and capital projects Steve Figueroa. This letter, according to Kelly, included a copy of the petition."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "In 2019, 81st district assembly person Dinowitz went to 555 Kappock St. to hear tenant comments and concerns, and the Baker Athletic Complex lights were one of several topics of discussion. At this meeting, Kelly said she presented the assembly person with a copy of the petition. Still, Kelly said no progress concerning the Baker lights came from this meeting."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "After two years of contact, Kelly, board member Maria Tsirkas, and board president Bonnie Press scheduled a meeting with Community and Government Relations Director Sandra Harris in October 2019. In this meeting, Kelly presented Harris with the petition. Tskiras said in this meeting they also learned 555 Kappock was not the only building to contact Columbia with complaints of light pollution."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“We got the usual ‘Well, yes, we’re very sorry, and we’ll get back to you,’” Tsirkas said. “Of course, they never got back to us. Again, we emailed her, we called, no response.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "On behalf of 555 Kappock tenants, Press followed up with Harris via email in November 2019 and again in January and March of 2020. An email on Nov. 18, 2019 included three weeks of daily reports on the on and off times of the soccer and football field lights. Still, she received no response."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "In March 2020 and the onset of the COVID-19 pandemic, advocacy efforts came to a halt, but even after years of effort, Kelly said she has seen no progress."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“Nothing, nothing changed,” Kelly said. “We had asked for things like a retrofitting of the lights because the lights can be changed so that they focus on the field, not so much outside the field and shine into our windows. And we had asked that the lights only be on when there was activity on the field. But nothing changed. The lights still would be beaming in the middle, there’s no one on the field, no game, no single person running the track. No one.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "With the exception of a decrease during COVID-19 pandemic-related closures, Kelly said, the frequency and intensity of the lights at Columbia’s Baker Athletic Complex  have not improved since 2017."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“I always loved Columbia,” Ortiz said. “But I just feel like living here, I’ve lost a little bit of respect for the school because I just think it’s rude. And I think that ignoring all of these residents’—especially seniors’—petitions and requests is rude. It’s not being a good neighbor.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "After years of time, energy, and dismissal, Kelly hopes Columbia finally modifies their lighting and acknowledges the needs of the communities it impacts."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“I would like Columbia to take responsibility for their lights and where they shine,and when they shine, and make it their business to assure all residents that their lights are not shining in[to] our windows,” Kelly said."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "<i>Staff writer Amira McKee can be contacted at amira.mckee@columbiaspectator.com.</i>"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "<b><i>Want to keep up with breaking news? Subscribe to our </i></b><a href=\"https://columbiaspectator.us4.list-manage.com/subscribe?u=a3d2eeb1ae5560ca04f82f042&id=e51c51d62d\"><b><i>email newsletter </i></b></a><b><i>and like Spectator on </i></b><a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/columbiaspectator\"><b><i>Facebook</i></b></a><b><i>. </i></b>"
            }
          ],
          "page_1": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "The 1984 Columbia football team needed a win—badly. With its last winning"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "season dating back to 1971, morale among players was low. But as the contemporary reasoning went, that was all about to change, since Lawrence A. Wien Stadium was opening that fall, replacing the rotting, wooden Baker Field with 10,500 shiny seats and a losing streak with newfound optimism."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“The sight is an awesome one,” <a href=\"https://spectatorarchive.library.columbia.edu/?a=d&d=cs19840411-01.2.20&srpos=9&e=------198-en-20--1--txt-txIN-wien+stadium----1984%e2%80%93--\">an April 1984 Spectator article</a> reads, anticipating the completion of the stadium. “Rising from the spot where the former wooden Baker Field once stood, a grand and new stadium is taking shape.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“More than a football stadium opens tomorrow,” <a href=\"https://spectatorarchive.library.columbia.edu/?a=d&d=cs19840921-01.2.25&srpos=2&e=------198-en-20--1--txt-txIN-wien+stadium----1984%e2%80%93--\">another Spectator article from September of the same year states. </a>“Coaches, players, alumni and fans expect that the day will mark the opening of a new and more successful chapter in Columbia football.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Now, 38 years later, a different part of the Baker Athletics Complex is due for an upgrade: the Dick Savitt Tennis Center. Built in 2002, the facility is considered outdated and out of touch with the University’s athletic needs, much like Baker Field was in the 1980s. The demolition of the Dick Savitt Tennis Center and construction of a new facility in its stead is part of an ongoing process to modernize Baker, which is located in Inwood, Manhattan and occupies 21 acres of northern Manhattan."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Construction by the University often creates friction with the local community—the <a href=\"https://www.columbiaspectator.com/news/2022/04/11/cba-educational-benefits-scarcely-known-within-west-harlem-community-members-say/\">Manhattanville expansion in Morningside Heights and West Harlem</a> has, for example, long been a source of tension. The building of the new tennis center, however, has gone relatively smoothly, according to Sandra Harris, the associate vice president of government and community affairs at the Columbia University Irving Medical Center and Eleazar Bueno, the chairman of Community Board 12, which covers Washington Heights and West Harlem."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“Whenever we have these University projects, [I] make sure … that we bring the community to the table in a timely manner,” Harris said. “Making sure that they know exactly what is going to happen in their own communities.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Harris serves as a liaison between faculty members and the community and has developed relationships with many community organizations and engages with a host of issues, from housing, to food security, to Columbia-related plans."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "According to Harris, the University brought CB12 into talks about the tennis center early on in the project. The University revealed the plans for the new center at a CB12 Land Use Committee meeting on June 7, with the updated structure slated to open this fall. The new building is in the same footprint as the Dick Savitt Tennis Center and will rise less than 15 feet higher than the old facility. Additionally, it is being built “as of right,” which means that it complies with all zoning regulations and does not need to get supplemental approval from local community boards."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Though the new building will be built on the same plot of land as the now-obsolete Dick Savitt Tennis Center, its construction impacts Inwood residents, as Columbia’s decisions regarding Baker have long rippled out into the northern Manhattan community."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Ronald Blum, CC ’83, was a sports reporter for Spectator during his time at Columbia and wrote about a slate of renovations being made at Baker Field in the 1980s, which included both the construction of Wien Stadium and the potential sale of five acres of Baker land to Presbyterian Hospital, a matter of great controversy at the time. Some maintained that the sale violated the terms of the initial agreement regarding Baker’s land. In 1921, the financier George Baker gifted the University $700,000 to buy the property “on the sole condition that it is used for the purposes which you described to me,” which was athletics. In 1984, however, Columbia sold the land, on which Presbyterian built a 300-bed community hospital."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "While plenty of University students opposed the sale—<a href=\"https://spectatorarchive.library.columbia.edu/?a=d&d=cs19840217-01.2.8&srpos=8&e=------198-en-20--1--txt-txIN-------\">a 1984 Spectator editorial argued that the entire field was an integral part of Columbia’s athletic past and future</a>—many Inwood residents were also against it, as Blum reported. According to <a href=\"https://spectatorarchive.library.columbia.edu/?a=d&d=cs19821206-01.2.39&srpos=17&e=------198-en-20--1--txt-txIN-------\">an article he wrote in 1982,</a> community activists delivered over 1,000 letters written by “alumni, students, faculty, and neighbors” opposing the sale to the University. <a href=\"https://www.nytimes.com/1982/11/09/nyregion/hospital-trying-to-buy-5-acres-of-baker-field.html\">The New York Times reported</a> that many residents supported the construction of a community hospital, but worried that building it at Baker would cause parking problems, a fear that Blum remembers well."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“You find, especially in the community, the main fear is traffic and the impact on the community,” Blum, who grew up in Inwood, said. Yet, he does not believe that students were generally attuned to the questions that community members were raising in the 1980s or that they are generally attuned to those questions now."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“The athletes for the most part took the bus up at two, had practice on the field, then went back down,” Blum said. “On campus, Columbia then and now is really divorced from the community in large respects.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Indeed, the relationship between Columbia and the Inwood community is not only characterized by less interaction with students but also by a different type of intimacy with faculty, which is illustrated in the construction of the new tennis center."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Harris was raised in Washington Heights and has worked with the Inwood community and its stakeholders for the past 35 years. In that time, she has developed personal connections with many community leaders and is working to build what she calls “mutually beneficial relationships.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“It’s a very intimate relationship with our community members,” Harris said. “And I say intimate because a lot of times they know that I’m going to share the truth. … They also feel comfortable coming to the table and saying, ‘You know, Sandra, we … disagree.’”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Among those “at the table” is Bueno, who has lived in Washington Heights for 20 years; his main job, he says, is to make sure that his community benefits from any decision Columbia makes. When it comes to communicating about and with Columbia, Harris is his main point of contact."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“There’s some confidence and trust factor, and that is Sandra,” Bueno said. “She’s been a good ally. She’s born [here], so she knows our wants and needs.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "The relationship between Harris and Inwood residents, including Bueno, seems to be markedly different than that between the University and the Morningside Heights community, which many residents associate with<a href=\"https://www.columbiaspectator.com/news/2022/04/11/cba-educational-benefits-scarcely-known-within-west-harlem-community-members-say/\"> murky communication and a lack of trust</a> rather than sustained dialogue."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Harris said that when residents have concerns—mainly revolving around traffic and construction noise, consistent with what Blum identified as contentious in the 1980s—they generally reach out to her, creating what Bueno described as “integrative and collaborative” communication. Some were likewise concerned about the lighting on the roof of the new center, which will house the six outdoor courts, as lighting at the football field has also been an issue. The tennis center lights, however, will largely reflect into the water, rather than at residential buildings."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Aware of the concerns, Harris updates community members about the construction schedule every two weeks; she explained that since Columbia hires its own contractors, the school is able to stipulate the precise hours during which they work."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Bueno has not heard many complaints about traffic or construction times and is confident that he would have heard had there been significant issues. Yet, he does not attribute the smooth construction and communication to the University, which he describes as “abstract,” but rather to Harris herself."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“[Corporations] don’t speak, they don’t feel, they don’t have any emotions,” Bueno said. “They’re not humans, they’re entities. Therefore, they’re always going to look out for their own interest. … So the key has been to have a person that humanizes the processes. When you humanize, … things work to the benefit of the communities.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "All spaces in Baker are available for community use, and organizations will often host events, like school field days and the Inwood Film Festival, at these facilities. Yet, despite the technical accessibility of facilities like the tennis center, some wonder whether Columbia’s presence in Inwood is largely relevant to residents’ lives."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Chris Acosta, SEAS ’25, is from Washington Heights and questions if Baker is actually accessible to community members."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“Columbia, the football stadium, is only for Columbia,” Acosta said. “I never see other people in it. … If you’re going to make something, I think it would be really nice … at least make it that kind of public area.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Bueno, despite the positive relationship he has with Harris, agrees that Baker facilities do not always cater to residents’ interests. While the new tennis center will offer memberships, just as the Dick Savitt Tennis Center did, he questions whether many community members will buy one, as few are particularly invested in tennis."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“I’m not going to say this is purposely exclusive,” Bueno said. “What I am going to say is that Columbia is an Ivy League school, so they are going to develop and sponsor and promote the sports program that caters to the people they want.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "The construction of a new tennis center at Baker has not only illuminated the potential efficacy of engaging in hyper-local, interpersonal relationships with residents, but also raised new considerations about Baker’s impact. Though the new tennis facility will occupy the same land as the Dick Savitt Center, the renewed focus on Baker—which the University has been upgrading throughout the past decade—-raises questions about Columbia’s current and future presence in Inwood."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“Washington Heights, you see, is already pretty segregated,” Acosta said. “If you start building this whole Columbia thing, [many of the] people that live there … are going to be crammed into this not-so-great space while Columbia is taking up all of the nice space.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "<i>Deputy City News Editor Alice Tecotzky can be contacted at alice.tecotzky@columbiaspectator.com. Follow her on Twitter </i><a href=\"https://twitter.com/ATecotzky\"><i>@ATecotzky.</i></a>"
            },
            {
